segments.text: So you had some students also from Arkansas.
But second to Texas, the largest numbers came from Louisiana.
Yeah, out-of-state students.
And was there a difference between the quality of the out-of-state and the in-state students?
Oh, no.
The Louisiana boys were really good.
Actually, Louisiana picked their own students, you see.
They had to pay an out-of-state fee.
And then that southern college
Combine, whatever it was, anyway, the states without schools paid a certain amount for each out-of-state student accepted it.
Texas A&M, so Louisiana boys were uniformly good.
But then when they put in the two-year prerequisite, I mean, yeah, and
Then the court system, where we got up to where we had three or four boys, or three or four people, I should say, applying for each place.
That means when a boy does get accepted, he don't fool around.
If you waited two or three years to get in school, you're not going to throw it away for one Saturday night beer bust.
As far as the age of the students were concerned, you went to Kansas State at an older age than most of the students.
Were most of the students here back in the 1940s young?
Oh, yes.
They were in their early 20s.
Once in a while, you'd have one 19, but most of them were 21, 22, 23.
And I don't know what percentage, but quite a few were people like county agents
Agricultural people that decided they wanted to be veterinarians.
Did you have any with former college?
Oh yeah, quite a few.
After the war in 1945, when the GI's came back, then when we really started to grow and when we really got uniformly good students, because we were
went into a lot of jam sessions about these veterans coming back and they'd been used to being men.
Of course, most of them, a lot of them were officers.
And they'd give us a lot of baloney about how we had to treat them.
Well, I never saw a better bunch of boys than those.
They were polite and they'd say, sir, when you call the roll.
And it wasn't difficult to,
pick out who was flunk, it's difficult to pick out who you're gonna give the honors to.
Dean Price out here graduated in 49, he was in the first class of the veterans.
They came in in 45 and then on, and then on for about four or five years while the veterans predominated.
And then I believe it was 1960, correct me on that if I'm wrong, and they opened it to the co-eds.
Might have been later.
But the girls were uniformed.
It seems a rather interesting aspect of Texas A&M that these young men came back from the military, many of them having been officers, and then they became corpsmen.
How did they respond to that?
I don't know.
You got me there.
Doesn't that seem rather strange?
Because the Corps itself seems to be a training ground to make officers.
I don't know, but I know they were good students.
I'd take a class of veterans any time over a bunch of kids just out of school.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
A great number of them were married and some of them had children and they were serious.
Very serious I would imagine.
Now back in 1888 the university named Dr. Mark Francis as associate professor of veterinarian sciences and the veterinarian for the experiment station
And he remained at Texas A&M for almost a half a century.
Did you have... June, June 1936, and I came here in February 1936.
Right, so...
I knew him five months.
You knew him for five months.
What were your, how did you meet him, do you remember?
Well, he was actually acting head of the Department of Veterinary Science and acting dean, Ned Payton.
Dr. Mark took over his active duties, and Dr. Smith took over him in the veterinary science.
But he was an active old man.
He came around and introduced himself to me the second day I was there.
He said he hoped I liked it here.
What were your first impressions?
Oh, I loved him.
He was about my size.
In fact, he was near enough my size that I sat in for the photographer or the artist when they painted the pictures.
for Dr. Francis.
What do you think, although you only knew him for five months, did you have much of an opportunity to get to know him and could you comment about his character or just the type of personality he was?
Oh he was, well you couldn't help but like him and he had a keen brain.
He'd ask you searching questions.
The trouble was he was almost totally deaf.
Oh.
And he had trouble communicating.
For that reason, he talked a lot rather than letting you talk.
Incidentally, you may wonder how I'm talking to you now, but I had a double ear operation in 1960.
So I removed the interstates and I got rid of my hearing aids.
Oh, good, good.
Yeah, I was wondering that.
That's great.
So Dr. Francis was almost deaf, too.
Was he deaf?
Was this a...
I don't know the clinical aspects of it.
Oh, okay.
That's what I was going to ask.
That's what I was going to ask.
Okay, clinical.
But Dr. Francis single-handedly
developed the immunization for Texas fever, rather pre-immunization.
He single-handedly sold Texas on the fact they had to get rid of the tick.
And he single-handedly started the School of Medicine, that old school over there now where the engineers had it.
In the depth of depression in 1932, he went over to the legislature and single-handedly got that appropriation.
So Texas owes a wonderful debt to Dr. Francis.
And yet, as far as I know, he never really antagonized anybody.
He sold them on lodging.
But he was a smart veterinarian.
He was a highly intelligent man.
That's a better way to put it.
You said that there was something about him that was very likable.
Why?
Or what was it?
Oh, I don't know.
That little fly grin and his sense of humor.
Mm-hmm.
Good sense of humor.
He had a wonderful sense of humor.
Mm-hmm.

I remember he was telling me about one time he come up there and he just found a little piece of paper where somebody back in Ohio or Minnesota or someplace had figured the world was formed 1,890 years ago at 9 o'clock in the morning.
He looked at me, he just giggled and said, 9 o'clock.
Now I've been more like it.
Walked off.
You know, he was originally from Ohio and did his college at Ohio State.
Did he ever say anything about?
why he stayed for so long in Texas.
I mean, after he began to establish this.
Well, I think he took it as a challenge.
And not only that, but the first faculty members of Texas A&M were from Ohio State.
Dr. Mark Duller came in 1905, and Dr. Dunn came in 1911.
D.W. Williams was an agriculture, an Ohio stater.
And
Penn versus Ohio State.
In fact, for years, the curriculum of Texas A&M was almost identical to that of Ohio State.
Is that because Ohio State was recognized as the leader?
No, I think it's primarily because Dr. Dunn, Dr. Mark Taylor, and Dr. Francis were from Ohio State.
Of course, you always think your old home state's the best.
Sure, sure.
Mm-hmm.
What were the finest veterinary colleges in the country back at that time?
Well, I couldn't be prejudiced.
I'd say Kansas State, but actually Cornell and Ohio and Iowa probably were the three, the big three.
Philadelphia was a private school.
In other words, it wasn't state supported like Yale and Harvard and, you know,
But Texas, see, graduated its first class in 1920, and those other schools had 20 years or so more than that.
Dr. Francis graduated in 1888.
So they had a lot longer to... Sure, to develop a program.
There were a lot of other important people who were instrumental in the early years of the School of Veterinarians.
And I'd like you to comment on some of these people, like Marsteller, Ross Perry Marsteller.
Well, Dr. Marsteller was dedicated to making this, the Bascule in the United States.
Dr. Marks had a way sometimes of rubbing people the wrong way.
In his later years, he was not in very good health.
And I think he antagonized people sometimes when he didn't mean to.
Dr. Dunn was just as dedicated, but he was quiet and easygoing.
And really, I think he did as much or more as any of them to keep a level of academic excellence.
He was a scholar, really, too.
And what about Marsdall?
Was he a scholar?
Well, I really didn't know him that well.
I was busy keeping out of Dr. Schmidt's way.
Yeah, let's talk about him.
Let's talk about Herbert Schmidt for a while.
Hubert, Hubert.
Hubert, Hubert, yes.
Could you tell me about him?
Well,
Darcy Smith was a big man.
He was six foot plus and weighed around 200 pounds, 220.
He graduated in animal husbandry from Texas A&M and was on the football team and played 60 minutes of every game.
And he was a native.
He was born to German immigrants near Comfort, Texas.
And Dr. Francis took a liking to him.
He asked him why he didn't go to Berlin, because at that time, before the war, Berlin, Germany, was topped on medicine and chemistry and a hell of a lot of other things.
So with Dr. Francis urging, Smith went to Germany and took
a degree in veterinary medicine over there.
And he came back and Dr. Francis put him in charge of all research work for it.
And veterinary science for the station.
And Dr. Smith was methodical.
And he had a brain, he was smart, there's no question about that.
But he just had one fault.
He didn't believe it unless he read it in German first.
Due to his German background.
The first thing he told me when I started working for him was I'd better learn to read German and I did.
Really?
Yeah, I read German.
I never could pronounce it like he wanted me to.
What type of administrator was he?
Well, he wasn't too good because he was a perfectionist.
A perfectionist is hard to work for.
In other words,
It's like I say, not like I do, you know.
But I had no trouble with him.
I worked for nine years.
I left because... Another opportunity.
Yeah.
What about the type of administrators at Marsdell and Dunn were?
Well, Dr. Marsdeller, maybe I shouldn't say this because he's dead, but
He liked to keep everybody just a little afraid of him.
He had a tendency to yell when a whisperer would have probably done better.
Oh, I see.
But he worked like the devil for the school.
There was no doubt about that.
He kept going through those years when we had no appropriations.
He'd scrunch and knock around corners and whatnot to get the job done.
And what about Dunn?
Oh, Dunn, everybody loved him.
He had no trouble in the department at all.
In fact, I think they gave Dunn a dirty deal, and they made him dean, and then later they burned him out, and put Dunn back, and almost broke his heart.
What happened there?
I'm not aware of this episode.
Well, when Dr. Marksteller died, they made Dr. Dean Dunn.
And evidently the powers that be, I don't know the ins and outs of it, because I never was much for politics.
I tried to stay out of their way.
Why?
They brought in Dr. Boughton from Sonora and made him Dean.

returned Dr. Dunn to his department of bacteriology and it was a kind of a shock because he only had three or four more years to go but he never he would he was kind of reminded to get his feelings hurt and I guess I would have too sure and if he hadn't been old if he hadn't been
As old as he was, he probably would have picked up and left, but nobody wants to hire a man sixty-two or three years old.
How about Van Bauchenberg?
Well, Van Bauchenberg was a Cornell graduate, and he came here from Puerto Rico, where he had been in charge of experimentation down there, and he was really a nice guy.
but he had bad luck physically.
Hi, how are you?
This is Mr. Anderson, that's my wife.
Glad to meet you.
And so he came from Puerto Rico.
To Texas.
See, the Department of Veterinary Affairs dogs were just established that year.
Before that, they'd all been lumped under Dr. Dunn.
What kind of man was Van Bakken?
Well, he was a
A gentleman never meaning a word, that's the only thing I can say.
He was quiet spoken, but he had trouble physically.
He had a busted appendix and he was in the hospital for several months.
And that's the time that I started teaching parastology, you know, filling in the gaps.
And then he died suddenly of a heart attack.
He never was, he never was strong physically after.
But he was quite interested.
He was a working member of the Baptist Church, secretary of the Rotary Club, and the boys liked him very well.
But he was kind of like Dr. Dunn.
He was soft-spoken.
He didn't make much noise.
I personally thought he was one of the best friends I had.
He was, he was keen on Lexi.
He was smart.
Then his boy got killed in the war.
He was a waist gunner on a bomber.
That must have been a terrible shock.
Sort of dropped him down more.
So really, there's not too much to say about Van Volkenberg.
He just did his job and didn't make any waves.
OK, I think that we should continue and bring the story from the 1940s up until you retired in the 1960s.
But let's do that next time we talk.
All right.
All right?
Fine.
OK, this ends our interview then.
This is an interview with Dr. RT Turk.
Interview number two.
Today's date is January 17, 1980.
This is Terry Anderson.
This is the second interview with Dr. Turk.
on Thursday, January 17th, 1980.
This is Terry Anderson.
Let's start this by talking about the changes in curriculum.
Well, to understand that, we'll have to have a little bit of history.
When World War I broke out, the Army needed buttonheads.
And they were
rather disgruntled to find that many of the local, many of the practicing veterinarians were inadequately educated.
The reason for that was that most of the veterinary schools were private schools.
There were only about six or eight schools in the United States that offered the veterinary degree, but they were
25 or 30 or possibly more private veterinary schools.
Some of these had only the equivalent of college education, others only the equivalent of being able to read or write.
Some of them had a six-month course and some of them had three years.
Another thing that happened that no one was interested in veterinary education anymore because there weren't going to be any more horses.
In 1914, Ford perfected his assembly line, and World War I came along, and planes and cars and so forth were the wave of the future.
So the National Defense Act of 1920, among other things, stipulated
the requirements for a veterinarian who would be eligible for government service.
That included not only the Army, but also the United States Department of Agriculture with its meat inspectors and the quarantine service with its animal health inspectors.
Very few of the, well actually none of the private veterinary schools could meet the requirements.
So they closed one by one.
Why couldn't they meet those requirements?
Well, for the expense.
They required English and history and bacteriology and pathology and many things besides purely clinical veterinary medicine.
But nobody cared because there weren't going to be any use for veterinarians anymore anyway.
In 1929, the first purely small animal hospital was established in Kansas City by a man named Dr. Flynn.
How do you spell that?
F-L-Y-N-N. Who could not do large animal practice because he had a wooden leg.
The demand for veterinarians were so slim that the University of Georgia closed their school down.
And the veterinarians that were eligible to graduate came to Kansas State and various other colleges.
They just deported them out.
In 1929, Texas A&M graduated one student.
Dr. W.T.
Hardy in the House of Nora, Texas.
In 1933, the year I graduated from Kansas State, Texas A&M only graduated four students.
Dr. J.W.
Dollahy was one of those.
Then, along about 1938 or 1939, the public awakened to the fact that
The average age of all veterinary in the United States was about 55 or 56 years old, and there would soon be an acute shortage.
So the trend on veterinary medicine picked up.
About that time, the boys on the East Coast, particularly from New York, found out they could go to Google Keeper in Texas
Georgia and Alabama and even Colorado and Washington than they could in New York.
So we had the influx of students.
So in 1939, they put in the requirement that students could come only from the state in which school was located or from adjoining states.
Was that a state requirement or a Texas A&M requirement?
It was a state requirement all across, all the colleges went in and joined because I think we had I believe 79 students in 1939 of which purely 50% were from New York City.
Really?
50% from New York City?
They were from Upper New York.
Even then, the pressure on veterinary faculty to take care of the students that applied mattered.
they began to stiffen their requirement for entrance.
I noticed in 1936 there was a new requirement established for entrance into the vet school.
You had to have 15 hours of pre-professional college work.
Now, what impact did that have on the student body?
That had really much more limit than they anticipated.
But it did.
Limited the amount of students much more than they anticipated?
Much less than they anticipated.
Oh, much less than they anticipated, okay.
Because many of the applicants at that time had already had two years in agriculture or quite a few of them even had BS degrees in agriculture, so all year related biological sciences.
Then they went along, though, until 1941 when the war broke out.
And again, the veterinary schools were fighting for students.
However, I forget when Georgia reopened their school, but anyway,
No more schools went down.
Was the school in Georgia or was it a Georgia Tech?
It was the University of Georgia at Athens.
Then in 1945, the war was over and the first crop of veterans came in.
Again, many more students applied than were
able to be accommodated.
So the various colleges got together and put in a pre-veterinary, how do you call it?
Curriculum.
No, prerequisite.
Oh, prerequisite.
In reality, it meant two years pre-vet.
Right.
Even that didn't stop.
the veterinary students.
So... Was this the American Veterinarian Association that got together and... No, the... Or was it an intercollegiate?
It was intercollegiate.
Mm-hmm.
With, of course, the approval and blessing of the AVMA, but the AVMA was only in advisory capacity.
Right.
Those fellows in Chicago can't tell.
It's like explaining to them how to run the school, you see.
Oh, absolutely.
Right.
But they do have a...
a so-called accredited list that you have to graduate from a certain type of school before you become a member of the AMMA.
Well, or rather to be from a college recognized by the AMMA.
So with the two-year prerequisite deal, many of the

subjects that before had been offered in veterinary school, like, for example, English, entomology, mathematics, physics, and so forth, were transferred to the two-year pre-vet school, and that allowed the veterinary school proper the four years of pre-professional training
to concentrate primarily on veterinary medicine and veterinary medicine alone.
So it was basically, after the Second World War, then it was basically switched to a six-year program.
Yes.
And so the curriculum was established by the Association of Veterinary Colleges, actually it's
an association of beings.
And...
